# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: uvicorn-asgi
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:uvicorn-asgi/asynchronous-server-gateway-interface] The **Asynchronous Server Gateway Interface** (**ASGI**) is a calling convention for web servers to forward requests to asynchronous-capable Python frameworks, and applications.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/asynchronous-server-gateway-interface] It is built as a successor to the Web Server Gateway Interface (WSGI).
[src:uvicorn-asgi/asynchronous-server-gateway-interface] Where WSGI provided a standard for synchronous Python applications, ASGI provides one for both asynchronous and synchronous applications, with a WSGI backwards-compatibility implementation and multiple servers and application frameworks.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/asynchronous-server-gateway-interface] ASGI is also designed to be a superset of WSGI, and there's a defined way of translating between the two, allowing WSGI applications to be run inside ASGI servers through a translation wrapper (provided in the asgiref library).
[src:uvicorn-asgi/asynchronous-server-gateway-interface] A threadpool can be used to run the synchronous WSGI applications away from the async event loop.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] In software, an **event loop** is an algorithm that continually dispatches control flow for events.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] The loop requests the next event from an event provider (which generally blocks the loop until an event occurs), and when an event is received, invokes its associated event handler.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] When the event loop is the central event dispatcher of a program, as it often is, it is called the **main loop** or **main event loop**.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] In modern environments such as web browsers and server runtimes, the event loop is a fundamental mechanism that enables asynchronous execution by continuously monitoring and dispatching events or messages from a queue when the main program thread is idle.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] In JavaScript, the event loop allows non-blocking handling of tasks such as user interactions, timers, and I/O operations despite the language being single-threaded.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] The same algorithm can be used to process inbound messages, a superset of events.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] In this context, the algorithm is called a **message loop**, **message dispatcher**, or **message pump**.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] A common use for a message loop is message passing inter-process communication where the message queue is maintained outside of the program (such as by the operating system).
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] Typically, a program that operates in a graphical user interface (GUI) environment uses an event loop, and due to the predominance of GUI environments, most modern applications have a main event loop.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] In the following pseudocode, `get_next_message()` is a placeholder for a function that is typically provided by the operating system that blocks until a message is available.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] Thus, the loop only repeats when there is a message to process.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] Many programs include an event loop in the high-level design; a main event loop, but there are alternative designs.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] A program can exit as soon as it completes the actions that it's designed to do without external (i.e. user) interaction.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] Often, such a program has optional behavior that is set up before the program starts such as via the command-line interface (CLI) or environment variables.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] Utility software is often of this nature.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] Even if a program provides for user interaction, it might not use an event loop.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] A program that provides an internal CLI does include a command processor that is similar to an event loop in that it dispatches to command handlers based on user input.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] A web page and its JavaScript typically run in a single-threaded web browser process.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] The browser process deals with messages from a queue one at a time.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] A JavaScript function or another browser event might be associated with a given message.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] When the browser process has finished with a message, it proceeds to the next message in the queue.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] In JavaScript environments, the event loop works with separate queues — including a task queue and a microtask queue — to manage asynchronous operations such as timers, promise callbacks, and DOM events.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] When the call stack is empty, the event loop selects the next task from these queues to execute.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] In Windows, a process that interacts with the user must accept and react to incoming messages, which is almost inevitably done by a message loop in that process.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] In Windows, a message is equated to an event created and imposed upon the operating system.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] An event can be user interaction, network traffic, system processing, timer activity, inter-process communication, among others.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] For non-interactive, I/O only events, Windows has I/O completion ports.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] I/O completion port loops run separately from the Message loop, and do not interact with the Message loop out of the box.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] The heart of most Win32 applications is the WinMain() function, which calls GetMessage() in a loop.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] GetMessage() blocks until a message (event), is received (with function PeekMessage() as a non-blocking alternative).
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] After some optional processing, it will call DispatchMessage(), which dispatches the message to the relevant handler, also known as WindowProc.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] Normally, messages that have no special WindowProc() are dispatched to DefWindowProc, the default one.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] DispatchMessage() calls the WindowProc of the HWND handle of the message (registered with the RegisterClass() function).
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] More recent versions of Windows guarantee that messages will be delivered to an application's message loop in the order that they were perceived by the system and its peripherals.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] This guarantee is essential when considering the design consequences of multithreaded applications.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] However, some messages have different rules, such as messages that are always received last, or messages with a different documented priority.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] X applications using Xlib directly are built around the `XNextEvent` family of functions; `XNextEvent` blocks until an event appears on the event queue, whereupon the application processes it appropriately.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] The Xlib event loop only handles window system events; applications that need to be able to wait on other files and devices could construct their own event loop from primitives such as `ConnectionNumber`, but in practice tend to use multithreading.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] In the more common case, GUI toolkits based on Xlib usually support adding events.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] For example, toolkits based on Xt Intrinsics have `XtAppAddInput()` and `XtAppAddTimeout()`.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] It is not safe to call Xlib functions from a signal handler, because the X application may have been interrupted in an arbitrary state, e.g. within `XNextEvent`.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] See [1] for a solution for X11R5, X11R6 and Xt.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] The GLib event loop was originally created for use in GTK but is now used in non-GUI applications as well, such as D-Bus.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] The resource polled is the collection of file descriptors the application is interested in; the polling block will be interrupted if a signal arrives or a timeout expires (e.g. if the application has specified a timeout or idle task).
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] Application libraries that are built on the GLib event loop include GStreamer and the asynchronous I/O methods of GnomeVFS, but GTK remains the most visible client library.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] Events from the windowing system (in X, read off the X socket) are translated by GDK into GTK events and emitted as GLib signals on the application's widget objects.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] Exactly one CFRunLoop is allowed per thread, and arbitrarily many sources and observers can be attached.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] Sources then communicate with observers through the run loop, with it organising queueing and dispatch of messages.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] The CFRunLoop is abstracted in Cocoa as an NSRunLoop, which allows any message (equivalent to a function call in non-reflective runtimes) to be queued for dispatch to any object.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] In Unix, the everything is a file paradigm leads to a file-based event loop.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] Reading from and writing to files, inter-process communication, network communication, and device control are all achieved using file I/O, with the target identified by a file descriptor.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] The select and poll system calls allow a set of file descriptors to be monitored for a change of state, e.g. when data becomes available to be read.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] In Unix, a signal is an asynchronous event that is handled by a signal handler which runs while the rest of the task is suspended.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] If a signal is received and handled while the task is blocking in `select()`, select will return early with EINTR; if a signal is received while the task is CPU bound, the task will be suspended between instructions until the signal handler returns.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] A way to handle a signal is for signal handlers to set a global flag and have the event loop check for the flag immediately before and after the `select()` call; if it is set, handle the signal in the same manner as with events on file descriptors.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] Unfortunately, this gives rise to a race condition: if a signal arrives immediately between checking the flag and calling `select()`, it will not be handled until `select()` returns for some other reason (for example, being interrupted by a frustrated user).
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] The solution arrived at by POSIX is the `pselect()` call, which is similar to `select()` but takes an additional `sigmask` parameter, which describes a *signal mask*.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] This allows an application to mask signals in the main task, then remove the mask for the duration of the `select()` call such that signal handlers are only called while the application is I/O bound.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] However, implementations of `pselect()` have not always been reliable; versions of Linux prior to 2.6.16 do not have a `pselect()` system call, forcing glibc to emulate it via a method prone to the very same race condition `pselect()` is intended to avoid.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] An alternative, more portable solution, is to convert asynchronous events to file-based events using the *self-pipe trick*, where "a signal handler writes a byte to a pipe whose other end is monitored by `select()` in the main program".
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] In Linux kernel version 2.6.22, a new system call `signalfd()` was added, which allows receiving signals via a special file descriptor.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] In environments such as web browsers and Node.js, the event loop is central to asynchronous program behavior.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] JavaScript runs on a single thread for execution, but host environments provide APIs for non-blocking operations, such as timers, network requests, and user events.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] Completed asynchronous operations are placed in queues, and the event loop repeatedly checks whether the call stack is empty to schedule queued callbacks.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/event-loop] This enables JavaScript applications to remain responsive while handling multiple asynchronous tasks.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/introduction] ASGI is a spiritual successor to WSGI, the long-standing Python standard for compatibility between web servers, frameworks, and applications.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/introduction] WSGI succeeded in allowing much more freedom and innovation in the Python web space, and ASGI’s goal is to continue this onward into the land of asynchronous Python.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/introduction] You may ask “why not just upgrade WSGI”?
[src:uvicorn-asgi/introduction] This has been asked many times over the years, and the problem usually ends up being that WSGI’s single-callable interface just isn’t suitable for more involved Web protocols like WebSocket.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/introduction] WSGI applications are a single, synchronous callable that takes a request and returns a response; this doesn’t allow for long-lived connections, like you get with long-poll HTTP or WebSocket connections.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/introduction] Even if we made this callable asynchronous, it still only has a single path to provide a request, so protocols that have multiple incoming events (like receiving WebSocket frames) can’t trigger this.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/introduction] ASGI is structured as a single, asynchronous callable.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/introduction] It takes a `scope`, which is a `dict` containing details about the specific connection, `send`, an asynchronous callable, that lets the application send event messages to the client, and `receive`, an asynchronous callable which lets the application receive event messages from the client.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/introduction] This not only allows multiple incoming events and outgoing events for each application, but also allows for a background coroutine so the application can do other things (such as listening for events on an external trigger, like a Redis queue).
[src:uvicorn-asgi/introduction] Every *event* that you send or receive is a Python `dict`, with a predefined format.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/introduction] It’s these event formats that form the basis of the standard, and allow applications to be swappable between servers.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/introduction] These *events* each have a defined `type` key, which can be used to infer the event’s structure.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/introduction] ASGI is also designed to be a superset of WSGI, and there’s a defined way of translating between the two, allowing WSGI applications to be run inside ASGI servers through a translation wrapper (provided in the `asgiref` library).
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] In computer networks, a **reverse proxy** or surrogate server is a proxy server that appears to any client to be an ordinary web server, but in reality merely acts as an intermediary that forwards the client's requests to one or more ordinary web servers.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies help increase scalability, performance, resilience, and security, but they also carry a number of risks.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] Companies that run web servers often set up reverse proxies to facilitate the communication between an Internet user's browser and the web servers.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] An important advantage of doing so is that the web servers can be hidden behind a firewall on a company-internal network, and only the reverse proxy needs to be directly exposed to the Internet.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxy servers are implemented in popular open-source web servers.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] Dedicated reverse proxy servers are used by some of the biggest websites on the Internet.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy is capable of tracking IP addresses of requests that are relayed through it as well as reading and/or modifying any non-encrypted traffic.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] However, this implies that anyone who has compromised the server could do so as well.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies differ from forward proxies, which are used when the client is restricted to a private, internal network and asks a forward proxy to retrieve resources from the public Internet.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] Large websites and content delivery networks use reverse proxies, together with other techniques, to balance the load between internal servers.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can keep a cache of static content, which further reduces the load on these internal servers and the internal network.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] It is also common for reverse proxies to add features such as compression or TLS encryption to the communication channel between the client and the reverse proxy.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can inspect HTTP headers, which, for example, allows them to present a single IP address to the Internet while relaying requests to different internal servers based on the URL of the HTTP request.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can hide the existence and characteristics of origin servers.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] This can make it more difficult to determine the actual location of the origin server / website and, for instance, more challenging to initiate legal action such as takedowns or block access to the website, as the IP address of the website may not be immediately apparent.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] Additionally, the reverse proxy may be located in a different jurisdiction with different legal requirements, further complicating the takedown process.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] Application firewall features can protect against common web-based attacks, like a denial-of-service attack (DoS) or distributed denial-of-service attacks (DDoS).
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] Without a reverse proxy, removing malware or initiating takedowns (while simultaneously dealing with the attack) on one's own site, for example, can be difficult.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] In the case of secure websites, a web server may not perform TLS encryption itself, but instead offload the task to a reverse proxy that may be equipped with TLS acceleration hardware.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can distribute the load from incoming requests to several servers, with each server supporting its own application area.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] In the case of reverse proxying web servers, the reverse proxy may have to rewrite the URL in each incoming request in order to match the relevant internal location of the requested resource.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can reduce load on its origin servers by caching static content and dynamic content, known as web acceleration.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] Proxy caches of this sort can often satisfy a considerable number of website requests, greatly reducing the load on the origin server(s).
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can optimize content by compressing it in order to speed up loading times.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] In a technique named "spoon-feeding", a dynamically generated page can be produced in its entirety and served to the reverse proxy, which can feed the page to the client as the connection allows.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] The program that generates the page need not remain open, thus releasing server resources during the possibly extended time the client requires to complete the transfer.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can operate wherever multiple web-servers must be accessible via a single public IP address.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] The web servers listen on different ports in the same machine, with the same local IP address or, possibly, on different machines with different local IP addresses.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] The reverse proxy analyzes each incoming request and delivers it to the right server within the local area network.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can perform A/B testing and multivariate testing without requiring application code to handle the logic of which version is served to a client.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can add access authentication to a web server that does not have any authentication.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] When the transit traffic is encrypted and the reverse proxy needs to filter/cache/compress or otherwise modify or improve the traffic, the proxy first must decrypt and re-encrypt communications.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] This requires the proxy to possess the TLS certificate and its corresponding private key, extending the number of systems that can have access to non-encrypted data and making it a more valuable target for attackers.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] The vast majority of external data breaches happen either when hackers succeed in abusing an existing reverse proxy that was intentionally deployed by an organization, or when hackers succeed in converting an existing Internet-facing server into a reverse proxy server.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] Compromised or converted systems allow external attackers to specify where they want their attacks proxied to, enabling their access to internal networks and systems.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] Applications that were developed for the internal use of a company are not typically hardened to public standards and are not necessarily designed to withstand all hacking attempts.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] When an organization allows external access to such internal applications via a reverse proxy, they might unintentionally increase their own attack surface and invite hackers.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] If a reverse proxy is not configured to filter attacks or it does not receive daily updates to keep its attack signature database up to date, a zero-day vulnerability can pass through unfiltered, enabling attackers to gain control of the system(s) that are behind the reverse proxy server.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] Giving the reverse proxy of a third party access to private keys (for caching or optimizing content) places the entire triad of confidentiality, integrity and availability in the hands of the third party who operates the proxy.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy is a single point of failure for the back-end services it fronts: an outage caused by misconfiguration, a denial-of-service attack, or a software fault can make every fronted service unreachable to outside clients, even when the back-end services themselves remain healthy.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/reverse-proxy] For example, a 2020 outage at Cloudflare briefly took down major sites and services that relied on its reverse-proxy edge, including Discord.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] This document proposes a standard interface between network protocol servers (particularly web servers) and Python applications, intended to allow handling of multiple common protocol styles (including HTTP, HTTP/2, and WebSocket).
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] This base specification is intended to fix in place the set of APIs by which these servers interact and run application code; each supported protocol (such as HTTP) has a sub-specification that outlines how to encode and decode that protocol into messages.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] The WSGI specification has worked well since it was introduced, and allowed for great flexibility in Python framework and web server choice.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] However, its design is irrevocably tied to the HTTP-style request/response cycle, and more and more protocols that do not follow this pattern are becoming a standard part of web programming (most notably, WebSocket).
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] ASGI attempts to preserve a simple application interface, while providing an abstraction that allows for data to be sent and received at any time, and from different application threads or processes.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] It also takes the principle of turning protocols into Python-compatible, asynchronous-friendly sets of messages and generalises it into two parts; a standardised interface for communication around which to build servers (this document), and a set of standard message formats for each protocol.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] Details on that interoperability are covered in the ASGI-HTTP spec.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] Like WSGI, the server hosts the application inside it, and dispatches incoming requests to it in a standardized format.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] Unlike WSGI, however, applications are asynchronous callables rather than simple callables, and they communicate with the server by receiving and sending asynchronous event messages rather than receiving a single input stream and returning a single iterable.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] ASGI applications must run as `async` / `await` compatible coroutines (i.e.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] `asyncio`-compatible) (on the main thread; they are free to use threading or other processes if they need synchronous code).
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] Applications are called and awaited with a connection `scope` and two awaitable callables to `receive` event messages and `send` event messages back.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] All this happening in an asynchronous event loop.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] Each call of the application callable maps to a single incoming “socket” or connection, and is expected to last the lifetime of that connection plus a little longer if there is cleanup to do.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] Some protocols may not use traditional sockets; ASGI specifications for those protocols are expected to define what the scope lifetime is and when it gets shut down.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] Every connection by a user to an ASGI application results in a call of the application callable to handle that connection entirely.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] How long this lives, and the information that describes each specific connection, is called the *connection scope*.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] Closely related, the first argument passed to an application callable is a `scope` dictionary with all the information describing that specific connection.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] For example, under HTTP the connection scope lasts just one request, but the `scope` passed contains most of the request data (apart from the HTTP request body, as this is streamed in via events).
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] Under WebSocket, though, the connection scope lasts for as long as the socket is connected.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] And the `scope` passed contains information like the WebSocket’s path, but details like incoming messages come through as events instead.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] Some protocols may give you a `scope` with very limited information up front because they encapsulate something like a handshake.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] Each protocol definition must contain information about how long its connection scope lasts, and what information you will get in the `scope` parameter.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] Depending on the protocol spec, applications may have to wait for an initial opening message before communicating with the client.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] ASGI decomposes protocols into a series of *events* that an application must *receive* and react to, and *events* the application might *send* in response.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] For HTTP, this is as simple as *receiving* two events in order - `http.request` and `http.disconnect`, and *sending* the corresponding event messages back.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] For something like a WebSocket, it could be more like *receiving* `websocket.connect`, *sending* a `websocket.send`, *receiving* a `websocket.receive`, and finally *receiving* a `websocket.disconnect`.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] Each event is a `dict` with a top-level `type` key that contains a Unicode string of the message type.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] Users are free to invent their own message types and send them between application instances for high-level events - for example, a chat application might send chat messages with a user type of `mychat.message`.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] It is expected that applications should be able to handle a mixed set of events, some sourced from the incoming client connection and some from other parts of the application.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] The application format changed in 3.0 to use a single callable, rather than the prior two-callable format.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] Two-callable is documented below in “Legacy Applications”; servers can easily implement support for it using the `asgiref.compatibility` library, and should try to support it.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] The application is called once per “connection”.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] The definition of a connection and its lifespan are dictated by the protocol specification in question.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] For example, with HTTP it is one request, whereas for a WebSocket it is a single WebSocket connection.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] Both the `scope` and the format of the event messages you send and receive are defined by one of the application protocols.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] The key `scope["type"]` will always be present, and can be used to work out which protocol is incoming.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] The key `scope["asgi"]` will also be present as a dictionary containing a `scope["asgi"]["version"]` key that corresponds to the ASGI version the server implements.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] If missing, the version should default to `"2.0"`.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] There may also be a spec-specific version present as `scope["asgi"]["spec_version"]`.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] This allows the individual protocol specifications to make enhancements without bumping the overall ASGI version.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] The protocol-specific sub-specifications cover these scope and event message formats.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] They are equivalent to the specification for keys in the `environ` dict for WSGI.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] The meanings of `scope`, `receive` and `send` are the same as in the newer single-callable application, but note that the first callable is *synchronous*.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] The first callable is called when the connection is started, and then the second callable is called and awaited immediately afterwards.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] This style was retired in version 3.0 as the two-callable layout was deemed unnecessary.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] It’s now legacy, but there are applications out there written in this style, and so it’s important to support them.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] There is a compatibility suite available in the `asgiref.compatibility` module which allows you to both detect legacy applications and convert them to the new single-protocol style seamlessly.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] Servers are encouraged to support both types as of ASGI 3.0 and gradually drop support by default over time.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] These describe the standardized scope and message formats for various protocols.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] The one common key across all scopes and messages is `type`, a way to indicate what type of scope or event message is being received.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] In scopes, the `type` key must be a Unicode string, like `"http"` or `"websocket"`, as defined in the relevant protocol specification.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] In messages, the `type` should be namespaced as `protocol.message_type`, where the `protocol` matches the scope type, and `message_type` is defined by the protocol spec.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] Examples of a message `type` value include `http.request` and `websocket.send`.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] Applications should actively reject any protocol that they do not understand with an *Exception* (of any type).
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] Failure to do this may result in the server thinking you support a protocol you don’t, which can be confusing when using with the Lifespan protocol, as the server will wait to start until you tell it.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] It is possible to have ASGI “middleware” - code that plays the role of both server and application, taking in a `scope` and the `send`/`receive` awaitable callables, potentially modifying them, and then calling an inner application.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] When middleware is modifying the `scope`, it should make a copy of the `scope` object before mutating it and passing it to the inner application, as changes may leak upstream otherwise.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] In particular, you should not assume that the copy of the `scope` you pass down to the application is the one that it ends up using, as there may be other middleware in the way; thus, do not keep a reference to it and try to mutate it outside of the initial ASGI app call.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] Your one and only chance to add to it is before you hand control to the child application.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] If a server receives an invalid event dictionary - for example, having an unknown `type`, missing keys an event type should have, or with wrong Python types for objects (e.g.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] Unicode strings for HTTP headers) - it should raise an exception out of the `send` awaitable back to the application.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] If an application receives an invalid event dictionary from `receive`, it should raise an exception.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] In both cases, the presence of additional keys in the event dictionary should not raise an exception.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] This allows non-breaking upgrades to protocol specifications over time.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] Servers are free to surface errors that bubble up out of application instances they are running however they wish - log to console, send to syslog, or other options - but they must terminate the application instance and its associated connection if this happens.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] Note that messages received by a server after the connection has been closed are generally not considered errors unless specified by a protocol.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] If no error condition is specified, the `send` awaitable callable should act as a no-op.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] Even if an error is raised on `send()`, it should be an error class that the server catches and ignores if it is raised out of the application, ensuring that the server does not itself error in the process.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] There are times when protocol servers may want to provide server-specific extensions outside of a core ASGI protocol specification, or when a change to a specification is being trialled before being rolled in.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] For this use case, we define a common pattern for `extensions` - named additions to a protocol specification that are optional but that, if provided by the server and understood by the application, can be used to get more functionality.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] This is achieved via an `extensions` entry in the `scope` dictionary, which is itself a `dict`.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] Extensions have a Unicode string name that is agreed upon between servers and applications.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] If the server supports an extension, it should place an entry into the `extensions` dictionary under the extension’s name, and the value of that entry should itself be a `dict`.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] Servers can provide any extra scope information that is part of the extension inside this value or, if the extension is only to indicate that the server accepts additional events via the `send` callable, it may just be an empty `dict`.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] As an example, imagine a HTTP protocol server wishes to provide an extension that allows a new event to be sent back to the server that tries to flush the network send buffer all the way through the OS level.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] If an application sees this it then knows it can send the custom event (say, of type `http.fullflush`) via the `send` callable.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] In this document, and all sub-specifications, *byte string* refers to the `bytes` type in Python 3.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] *Unicode string* refers to the `str` type in Python 3.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] This document will never specify just *string* - all strings are one of the two exact types.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] All `dict` keys mentioned (including those for *scopes* and *events*) are Unicode strings.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/specs-main] This document has been placed in the public domain.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/uvicorn] Pydantic is a data validation library for Python.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/uvicorn] While writing code in an IDE, Pydantic provides type hints based on annotations.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/uvicorn] FastAPI extensively utilizes Pydantic models for data validation, serialization, and automatic API documentation.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/uvicorn] These models are using standard Python type hints, providing a declarative way to specify the structure and types of data for incoming requests (e.g., HTTP bodies) and outgoing responses.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/uvicorn] Starlette is a lightweight ASGI framework/toolkit, to support async functionality in Python.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/uvicorn] Uvicorn is a minimal low-level server/application web server for async frameworks, following the ASGI specification.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/uvicorn] Technically, it implements a multi-process model with one main process, which is responsible for managing a pool of worker processes and distributing incoming HTTP requests to them.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/uvicorn] The number of worker processes is pre-configured, but can also be adjusted up or down at runtime.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/uvicorn] FastAPI automatically generates OpenAPI documentation for APIs.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/uvicorn] This documentation includes both Swagger UI and *ReDoc*, which provide interactive API documentation that you can use to explore and test your endpoints in real time.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/uvicorn] This is particularly useful for developing, testing, and sharing APIs with other developers or users.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/uvicorn] Swagger UI is accessible by default at **/docs** and ReDoc at **/redoc** route.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/uvicorn] FastAPI's architecture inherently supports asynchronous programming.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/uvicorn] This design allows the single-threaded event loop to handle a large number of concurrent requests efficiently, particularly when dealing with I/O-bound operations like database queries or external API calls.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/uvicorn] FastAPI incorporates a Dependency Injection (DI) system to manage and provide services to HTTP endpoints.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/uvicorn] This mechanism allows developers to declare components such as database sessions or authentication logic as function parameters.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/uvicorn] FastAPI automatically resolves these dependencies for each request, injecting the necessary instances.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/uvicorn] WebSockets allow full-duplex communication between a client and the server.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/uvicorn] This capability is fundamental for applications requiring continuous data exchange, such as instant messaging platforms, live data dashboards, or multiplayer online games.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/uvicorn] FastAPI leverages the underlying Starlette implementation, allowing for efficient management of connections and message handling.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/uvicorn] FastAPI enables the execution of background tasks after an HTTP response has been sent to the client.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/uvicorn] This allows the API to immediately respond to user requests while simultaneously processing non-critical or time-consuming operations in the background.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/uvicorn] Typical applications include sending email notifications, updating caches, or performing data post-processing.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] A **web server** is computer software that accepts requests via HTTP (the network protocol created to distribute web content) or its secure variant HTTPS.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] A user agent, commonly a web browser or web crawler, initiates communication by making a request for a web page or other resource using HTTP, and the server responds with the content of that resource or an error message.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] A web server can also accept and store resources sent from the user agent if configured to do so.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] The hardware used to run a web server can vary according to the volume of requests that it needs to handle.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] At the low end of the range are embedded systems, such as a router that runs a small web server as its configuration interface.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] A high-traffic Internet website might handle requests with hundreds of servers that run on racks of high-speed computers.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] A resource sent from a web server can be a pre-existing file (static content) available to the web server, or it can be generated at the time of the request (dynamic content) by another program that communicates with the server software.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] The former usually can be served faster and can be more easily cached for repeated requests, while the latter supports a broader range of applications.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] Technologies such as REST and SOAP, which use HTTP as a basis for general computer-to-computer communication, as well as support for WebDAV extensions, have extended the application of web servers well beyond their original purpose of serving human-readable pages.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] In March 1989, Sir Tim Berners-Lee proposed a new project to his employer CERN, with the goal of easing the exchange of information between scientists by using a hypertext system.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] The proposal titled *"HyperText and CERN"*, asked for comments and it was read by several people.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] In October 1990 the proposal was reformulated and enriched (having as co-author Robert Cailliau), and finally, it was approved.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] Those early browsers retrieved web pages written in a simple early form of HTML from web servers using a new basic communication protocol that was named HTTP 0.9.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] In August 1991 Tim Berners-Lee announced the *birth of WWW technology* and encouraged scientists to adopt and develop it.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] Soon after, those programs, along with their source code, were made available to people interested in their usage.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] Although the source code was not formally licensed or placed in the public domain, CERN informally allowed users and developers to experiment and further develop on top of them.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] Berners-Lee started promoting the adoption and the usage of those programs along with their porting to other operating systems.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] In December 1991, the **first web server outside Europe** was installed at SLAC (U.S.A.).
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] This was a very important event because it started trans-continental web communications between web browsers and web servers.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] In 1991–1993, CERN web server program continued to be actively developed by the www group, meanwhile, thanks to the availability of its source code and the public specifications of the HTTP protocol, many other implementations of web servers started to be developed.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] In April 1993, CERN issued a public official statement stating that the three components of Web software (the basic line-mode client, the web server and the library of common code), along with their source code, were put in the public domain.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] This statement freed web server developers from any possible legal issue about the development of *derivative work* based on that source code (a threat that in practice never existed).
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] At the beginning of 1994, the most notable among new web servers was NCSA httpd which ran on a variety of Unix-based OSs and could serve *dynamically generated content* by implementing the `POST` HTTP method and the CGI to communicate with external programs.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] These capabilities, along with the multimedia features of NCSA's Mosaic browser (also able to manage HTML FORMs in order to send data to a web server) highlighted the potential of web technology for publishing and distributed computing applications.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] At the beginning of 1995 those patches were all applied to the last release of NCSA source code and, after several tests, the Apache HTTP server project was started.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] At the end of 1994, a new commercial web server, named Netsite, was released with specific features.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] It was the first one of many other similar products that were developed first by Netscape, then also by Sun Microsystems, and finally by Oracle Corporation.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] In mid-1995, the first version of IIS was released by Microsoft for Windows NT OS.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] This marked the entry, in the field of World Wide Web technologies, of a commercial developer and vendor that has played and still is playing a key role on both sides (client and server) of the web.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] In the second half of 1995, CERN and NCSA web servers started to decline (in global percentage usage) because of the widespread adoption of new web servers which had a much faster development cycle along with more features, more fixes applied, and more performances than the previous ones.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] At the end of 1996, there were already over fifty known, different web-server-software programs that were available to everybody who wanted to own an Internet domain name or to host websites.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] Many of them lived only shortly and were replaced by other web servers.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] The publication of RFCs about protocol versions HTTP/1.0 (1996) and HTTP/1.1 (1997, 1999), forced most web servers to comply (not always completely) with those standards.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] The use of TCP/IP persistent connections (HTTP/1.1) required web servers both to increase the maximum number of concurrent connections allowed and to improve their level of scalability.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] Between 1996 and 1999, Netscape Enterprise Server and Microsoft's IIS emerged among the leading commercial options whereas among the freely available and open-source programs Apache HTTP Server held the lead as the preferred server (because of its reliability and its many features).
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] In those years there was also another commercial web server called Zeus (*now discontinued*) that was known as one of the fastest and most scalable web servers available on market, at least till the first decade of 2000s, despite its low percentage of usage.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] Apache resulted in the most used web server from mid-1996 to the end of 2015 when, after a few years of decline, it was surpassed initially by IIS and then by Nginx.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] Afterward IIS dropped to much lower percentages of usage than Apache (see also market share).
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] From 2005–2006, Apache started to improve its speed and its scalability level by introducing new performance features (e.g., event MPM and new content cache).
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] A few years after 2000 started, not only other commercial and highly competitive web servers (e.g., LiteSpeed) but also many other open-source programs such as Hiawatha, Cherokee HTTP server, Lighttpd, Nginx and other derived and related products also available with commercial support emerged.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] Within a year, these changes, on average, nearly tripled the maximum number of persistent connections that web servers had to manage.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] In 2015, RFCs published new protocol version [HTTP/2], and as the implementation of new specifications was not trivial at all, a **dilemma arose among developers of less popular web servers** (e.g., with a percentage of usage lower than 1% ..
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] 2%), about adding or not adding support for that new protocol version.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] In 2020–2021 the HTTP/2 dynamics about its implementation (by top web servers and popular web browsers) were partly replicated after the publication of advanced drafts of future RFC about HTTP/3 protocol.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] The following technical overview should be considered only as an attempt to give a few very *limited examples* about *some* features that may be implemented in a web server and *some* of the tasks that it may perform in order to have a sufficiently wide scenario about the topic.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] A **web server program** plays the role of a server in a client–server model by implementing one or more versions of HTTP protocol, often including the HTTPS secure variant and other features and extensions that are considered useful for its planned usage.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] Although web server programs differ in how they are implemented, most of them offer the following common features.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] These are **basic features** that most web servers usually have.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] A few other more **advanced** and popular **features** (*only a very short selection*) are the following ones.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] Once an HTTP request message has been decoded and verified, its values can be used to determine whether that request can be satisfied or not.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] This requires many other steps, including **security checks**.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] The term *URL normalization* refers to the process of modifying and standardizing a URL in a consistent manner.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] There are several types of normalization that may be performed, including the conversion of the scheme and host to lowercase.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] Among the most important normalizations are the removal of "." and ".." path segments and adding trailing slashes to a non-empty path component.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] One or more configuration files of web server may specify the mapping of parts of **URL path** (e.g., initial parts of file path, filename extension and other path components) to a specific URL handler (file, directory, external program or internal module).
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] Web server programs are able to translate an URL path (all or part of it), that refers to a physical file system path, to an absolute path under the target website's root directory.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] Website's root directory may be specified by a configuration file or by some internal rule of the web server by using the name of the website which is the host part of the URL found in HTTP client request.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] The web server appends the path found in requested URL (HTTP request message) and appends it to the path of the (Host) website root directory.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] On an Apache server, this is commonly `/home/www/website` (on Unix machines, usually it is: `/var/www/website`).
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] See the following examples of how it may result.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] The web server then reads the file, if it exists, and sends a response to the client's web browser.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] The response will describe the content of the file and contain the file itself or an error message will return saying that the file does not exist or its access is forbidden.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] The response will describe the content of the directory (list of contained subdirectories and files) or an error message will return saying that the directory does not exist or its access is forbidden.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] For a *dynamic request* the URL path specified by the client should refer to an existing external program (usually an executable file with a CGI) used by the web server to generate dynamic content.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] The web server executes that program, passing in the path-info and the query string `action=view&orderby=thread&date=2021-10-15` so that the program has the info it needs to run.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] (In this case, it will return an HTML document containing a view of forum entries ordered by thread from October 15, 2021).
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] In addition to this, the web server reads data sent from the external program and resends that data to the client that made the request.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] Once a request has been read, interpreted, and verified, it has to be managed depending on its method, its URL, and its parameters, which may include values of HTTP headers.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] That kind of content is called *static* because usually it is not changed by the web server when it is sent to clients and because it remains the same until it is modified (file modification) by some program.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] Response of static file content can be sped up by a **file cache**.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] Most used names for static index files are: `index.html`, `index.htm` and `Default.htm`.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] If a web server program receives a client request message with an URL whose path matches the file name of an existing *file* and that file is accessible by web server program and its attributes match internal rules of web server program, then web server program can send that file to client.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] Usually, for security reasons, most web server programs are pre-configured to serve only regular files or to avoid to use *special file types* like device files, along with symbolic links or hard links to them.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] The aim is to avoid undesirable side effects when serving static web resources.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] If a web server program is capable of **serving dynamic content** and it has been configured to do so, then it is able to communicate with the proper internal module or external program (associated with the requested URL path) in order to pass to it the parameters of the client request.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] After that, the web server program reads from it its data response (that it has generated, often on the fly) and then it resends it to the client program who made the request.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] In order to be able to communicate with its internal modules or external programs, a web server program must have implemented one or more of the many available **gateway interfaces** (see also Web Server Gateway Interfaces used for dynamic content).
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] The three **standard** and historical **gateway interfaces** are the following ones.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] An external CGI program is run by web server program for each dynamic request, then web server program reads from it the generated data response and then resends it to client.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] An external FastCGI program (it usually is a process) is started once by web server program or by some other program or process and then it waits for a network connection which is established permanently by web server; through that connection are sent the request parameters and read data responses.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] A web server program may be capable to manage the dynamic generation (on the fly) of a **directory index list** of files and sub-directories.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] If it cannot be generated an error is returned.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] Usage of dynamically generated *directory listings* is usually avoided or limited to a few selected directories of a website because that generation takes much more OS resources than sending a static index page.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] The main usage of *directory listings* is to allow the download of files (usually when their names, sizes, modification date-times or file attributes may change randomly and frequently) *as they are, without requiring to provide further information to requesting user*.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] In practice whenever there is content that may vary, depending on one or more parameters contained in client request or in configuration settings, then, usually, it is generated dynamically.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] Web server programs are able to send response messages as replies to client request messages.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] An error response message may be sent because a request message could not be successfully read or decoded or analyzed or executed.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] NOTE: the following sections are reported only as examples to help to understand what a web server, more or less, does; these sections are by any means neither exhaustive nor complete.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] When an error response or message is received by a client browser, then if it is related to the main user request (e.g., an URL of a web resource such as a web page) then usually that error message is shown in some browser window or message.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] Example 1: a URL path points to a **directory** name but it does not have a final slash '/' so web server sends a redirect to client in order to instruct it to redo the request with the fixed path name.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] Example 2: a whole set of documents has been **moved inside website** in order to reorganize their file system paths.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] Example 3: a whole set of documents has been **moved to a new website** and now it is mandatory to use secure HTTPS connections to access them.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] Above examples are only a few of the possible kind of redirections.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] A web server program is able to reply to a valid client request message with a successful message, optionally containing requested **web resource data**.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] If web resource data is sent back to client, then it can be **static content** or **dynamic content** depending on how it has been retrieved (from a file or from the output of some program or module).
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] In order to speed up web server responses by lowering average HTTP response times and hardware resources used, many popular web servers implement one or more content caches, each one specialized in a content category.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] In practice, nowadays, many web server programs include their own *userland* **file cache**, tailored for a web server usage and using their specific implementation and parameters.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] The wide spread adoption of RAID and fast solid-state drives (storage hardware with very high I/O speed) has slightly reduced but of course not eliminated the advantage of having a file cache incorporated in a web server.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] Dynamic content, output by an internal module or an external program, may not always change very frequently (given a unique URL with keys or parameters) and so, maybe for a while (e.g., from one second to several hours or more), the resulting output can be cached in RAM or even on a fast disk.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] Anyway, in most cases those kind of caches are implemented by external servers (e.g., reverse proxy) or by storing dynamic data output in separate computers, managed by specific applications (e.g., memcached), in order to not compete for hardware resources (CPU, RAM, disks) with web servers.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] A web server software can be either incorporated into the OS and executed in kernel space, or it can be executed in user space (like other regular applications).
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] Web servers that run in user-mode have to ask the system for permission to use more memory or more CPU resources.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] Not only do these requests to the kernel take time, but they might not always be satisfied because the system reserves resources for its own usage and has the responsibility to share hardware resources with all the other running applications.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] Executing in user mode can also mean using more buffer or data copies (between user-space and kernel-space) which can lead to a decrease in the performance of a user-mode web server.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] Nowadays almost all web server software is executed in user mode (because many of the aforementioned small disadvantages have been overcome by faster hardware, new OS versions, much faster OS system calls and new optimized web server software).
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] See also comparison of web server software to discover which of them run in kernel mode or in user mode (also referred as kernel space or user space).
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] In other words, a **web server should always be very responsive**, even under high load of web traffic, in order to keep **total user's wait** (sum of browser time + network time + **web server response time**) for a response **as low as possible**.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] Among the operating conditions, the **number** (1 ..
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] *n*) of **concurrent client connections** used during a test is an important parameter because it allows to correlate the **concurrency level** supported by web server with results of the tested performance metrics.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] ... used to implement a web server program, **can bias a lot the performances** and in particular the **scalability level** that can be achieved under **heavy load** or when using high end hardware (many CPUs, disks and lots of RAM).
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] In practice some web server software models may require more OS resources (specially more CPUs and more RAM) than others to be able to work well and so to achieve target performances.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p01] Performances of a web server are typically benchmarked by using one or more of the available automated load testing tools.
[src:uvicorn-asgi/web-server-p02] When a web server is near to or over its load limits, it gets **overloaded** and so it may become **unresponsive**.
